segments.text: Then we sort of fell into using faculty members extensively to do work which could just as well have been done by graduate students.
And now we're coming back to using graduate students more.
You think that's part of getting the system set up?
Probably, yeah.
And again, there are things where, while a graduate student, for instance, might be able to go out and interview a manufacturer and come back with the same
There's, again, the additional perspective that experience gives when the faculty member, the mature faculty member, could sit there and say, now what's this guy really saying?
The nuances.
Yeah.
What does he really mean when he says that?
And that's just something you get through experience.
Are there any points that you'd like to bring up for posterity that we haven't covered?
Well, I'd like to be able to look at it ten years from now and see if everything that we've planned to do actually worked out that way.
What do you have to say?

Oh, I would like to see InVent as a standalone organization with more flexibility to work in and out of the university, so that it would have to be self-supporting and free of state funding at that point.

And I would think that one located here in proximity to the university would, but having its own self-generated funds, would be far more flexible in working with the faculty, and as well as being able to reach out and hire consultants from around the state or around the country, around the world.
And I'd like to point with Pri to some cubic packages.
You know, somebody had to help Bill Hewitt and Dave Packer.
I don't know if I can duplicate Fred Terriman, but again, I think that there's something motivating in that direction.
Do you think ten years is about the time that you get self-supporting?
Well, that's a goal.
And again, I'd say if we can't do it in ten years, then there's something very, very wrong with what we're doing.
Although I talked to a fellow yesterday, I thought it was yesterday, last month, from University of Research in Tucson, Arizona.
And they were originally funded by the Cottrell Foundation to take university developments and license them.
They've been in business now for about 50 years, and it's about breaking even.
And 60% of their income is due to one patent.
So without that lucky hit, they'd be way behind.
On the other hand, because we're taking equity in businesses, we should be doing a lot better.
They're just taking the royalty.
And they're just dealing with university inventions?
Yeah.
But on a nationwide basis.
What we're doing, we're taking royalties also where it's appropriate, but we'll take shares of stock where that's appropriate.
As a result, we're not tied in to a given invention as much as we are tied into a business.
And what we say is, fine, we're helping you start this business based on such and such an invention, and we're going to take a royalty on that.
But that's not for the invention.
That's for starting the business.
And they'll say, well, for how long are you going to be royalty?
Forever.
Well, are you going to help us forever and ever?
Nope.
But you would have given us 10% of your stock if you'd asked for it.
And you'd be paying us dividends forever and ever on that stock, unless we sold it.
And that's basically what we're doing.
We're translating an equivalent issue of stock into a royalty payment, simply because you weren't intending to incorporate in the first place.
That's what we're doing.
But where it's clear that they're going to incorporate, we may want to take the stock.
You're trying to stimulate business in Texas.
Do you require that they cooperate in Texas?
Well, we would, yeah, if it were from out of state.
And we also require that they locate in Texas.
There are three big pieces to a deal.
One of them is the mentor and invention.
The next is the site of the business or occasion of the business.
The third is the source of the capital.
Ideally, all three of those would be Texan.
If you have to pick one that's most important, I would say that's the manufacturing location.
Second importance is the location of the inventor, and third would be the source of capital.
And if you're saying, well, I want to see direct employment, then it's obviously the source of the manufacturing location, isn't it?
So if it takes and came up to you and said, I want to start a business in Louisiana, it's going to be cheaper?
Not necessarily.
They may wind up that way.
Try talking them into bringing it to Texas?
Well, see what the benefit to Texas would be.
And we've had contacts from all over the world.
And when it's from out of state, we'd say, hey, look, if we're going to work with you, it's got to be Texas.
Now, it's still untrusted.
Yeah, yeah, yeah, fine, let's put it in writing.
Well, I'm not sure I'm going to do that.
Anything else you'd like to add?
No, I think that's about it.
All right, well, thank you for your time.
